¬∑ The field of data visualization has exhibited a rapid growth in recent
years due to the increased availability of data sets from various
sources such as the social web [1], automated data mining and
sensing [2], genomic and proteomic sequencing projects [3], etc.
¬∑ Significant interest within the scientific and visual design communities
in creating data visualizations that have an intrinsic aesthetic value [7, 8].
¬∑ The Processing language and environment [9] is a widely used tool
thanks to its simple API and extensible library architecture.
¬∑ Processing has been used in numerous data visualization projects
[10, 11], but it presents some performance limitations for generating
interactive visualizations from massive data sets.
To provide interactive visualization of massive data sets in
Processing, while keeping its focus on simplicity.
Two open source libraries which ease the creation of higher-
performance graphics applications in Processing that are seamlessly
integrated with each other, having the following features:
¬∑ Shaders in various formats, such as GLSL, Cg and CgFX.
¬∑ Arcball, walkthrough and third person camera modes.
¬∑ Built-in view frustum and back face culling routines.
¬∑ Keyboard shortcuts and camera profiles customization.
Our proof-of-concept framework is functional and it currently is
being used in several applications, as shown below. Future work
¬∑ To implement the scene hierarchy construction built-in the
libraries and to support other spatial subdivisions such as BSP's,
¬∑ To support k-dops and other bounding volumes for the geometry,
currently only bounding boxes and bounding spheres are supported.
¬∑ To support LODs in a per node basis and out-of-core techniques
to be able to visualize even more challenging data-sets.
